1
00:00:33,450 --> 00:00:36,898
My mother made me promise
to be an artist.

2
00:00:37,227 --> 00:00:40,968
She taught me that imagination
could take a person anywhere.

3
00:00:41,162 --> 00:00:43,138
Mine took me from Indiana...

4
00:00:43,339 --> 00:00:46,208
...to Broadway to Hollywood.

5
00:00:46,411 --> 00:00:47,818
She was right.

6
00:00:51,627 --> 00:00:53,536
- Hello, Lou.
- Mr. Kazan, how are you?

7
00:00:53,738 --> 00:00:56,586
- Good to see you.
- Good to see you, sir.

8
00:00:56,874 --> 00:00:59,591
- Otto. How are you?
- Good morning, sir.

9
00:00:59,786 --> 00:01:03,136
- Good morning, Mr. Kazan.
- Good morning, Miss Harris.

10
00:01:06,538 --> 00:01:08,677
You look beautiful, Julie.

11
00:01:10,090 --> 00:01:11,334
Thank you.

12
00:01:11,882 --> 00:01:14,184
- Perfect, Anna.
- Thank you, Mr. Kazan.

13
00:01:14,538 --> 00:01:17,287
- Let's film this, Mike.
- Yes, sir.

14
00:01:17,898 --> 00:01:19,011
What else do we have?

15
00:01:19,242 --> 00:01:21,960
- Raymond. Where is he?
- Let's clear.

16
00:01:22,443 --> 00:01:25,541
Good morning. Hello!
It's nice to see you again.

17
00:01:25,738 --> 00:01:28,291
Elia, good heavens,
they're shooting.

18
00:01:28,490 --> 00:01:30,629
It's okay.
We're not shooting with sound.

19
00:01:30,826 --> 00:01:33,193
Good. How are you?
Good morning, Anna.

20
00:01:33,386 --> 00:01:35,393
Julie, you look marvelous.

21
00:01:35,626 --> 00:01:37,382
Thank you. Good morning, Raymond.

22
00:01:37,609 --> 00:01:39,617
- Good morning, Mr. Massey.
- Good morning.

23
00:01:39,819 --> 00:01:41,859
Good morning. Lovely day.

24
00:01:42,058 --> 00:01:45,124
This is what he'll wear
in the birthday scene.

25
00:01:45,322 --> 00:01:46,729
I like the cloth.

26
00:01:46,922 --> 00:01:48,100
Just for you, Raymond.

27
00:01:48,298 --> 00:01:51,396
Do you think I'm back playing
Abe Lincoln in this get-up?

28
00:01:51,625 --> 00:01:53,600
Not at all.
It seems right to me.

29
00:01:53,802 --> 00:01:55,590
All right. It feels good.

30
00:01:55,786 --> 00:01:57,858
Thank you.
Let's shoot Mr. Massey next.

31
00:01:58,059 --> 00:01:59,204
Can I have one that works?

32
00:01:59,402 --> 00:02:03,198
Absolutely. We'll get Props on that.
Props, Mr. Massey needs you!

33
00:02:03,401 --> 00:02:05,344
I am so looking
forward to this.

34
00:02:05,547 --> 00:02:08,481
- So am I, Raymond. So am I.
- Good.

35
00:02:08,683 --> 00:02:11,617
- Do you want this smiling or natural?
- Natural.

36
00:02:11,817 --> 00:02:14,086
I wanted to call you last night.

37
00:02:14,282 --> 00:02:17,927
I wanted to tell you how wonderful
you were in rehearsals.

38
00:02:18,123 --> 00:02:20,294
Just so beautifully...
Just very pleased.

39
00:02:20,491 --> 00:02:24,931
- I think we've broken through.
- Oh, yes. I do too.

40
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:26,664
James Dean is here.

41
00:02:26,857 --> 00:02:28,647
Send him in.

42
00:02:28,842 --> 00:02:30,403
Be right back.

43
00:02:30,762 --> 00:02:32,999
Raymond, let's stop this for a moment.

44
00:02:33,322 --> 00:02:34,816
Sorry, everybody.

45
00:02:35,563 --> 00:02:38,944
The boy I've cast as Cal is coming in
and I'd like you to meet him.

46
00:02:39,146 --> 00:02:40,805
Well, I'd be happy to.

47
00:02:41,163 --> 00:02:43,235
He's never done a feature before.

48
00:02:43,466 --> 00:02:47,874
He's done some first-rate stage
and TV work. He's a natural.

49
00:02:48,458 --> 00:02:51,840
He may strike you as odd,
but he's enormously talented.

50
00:02:52,106 --> 00:02:54,015
Well, let's take a look.

51
00:02:54,891 --> 00:02:56,167
Jimmy.

52
00:02:56,746 --> 00:02:59,015
Jimmy, come meet Raymond Massey.

53
00:02:59,210 --> 00:03:02,112
- Oh, he's probably shy.
- Come on.

54
00:03:02,697 --> 00:03:03,941
All right.

55
00:03:13,387 --> 00:03:16,485
This man can't play my father.
He's too old.

56
00:03:17,226 --> 00:03:19,299
Get somebody else.

57
00:03:25,098 --> 00:03:28,196
- I'll talk to him. I'll talk to him.
- What-

58
00:03:38,825 --> 00:03:40,451
What the hell
were you thinking in there?

59
00:03:41,418 --> 00:03:45,695
Raymond Massey is a highly respected
actor and you've offended him.

60
00:03:46,090 --> 00:03:49,766
- He said I offended him?
- Of course you deeply offended him.

61
00:03:50,185 --> 00:03:51,298
Good.

62
00:03:53,386 --> 00:03:54,334
Why good?

63
00:03:56,746 --> 00:03:58,885
Because I need him to hate me.

64
00:04:12,682 --> 00:04:14,982
Yeah, we're still a little hot.

65
00:04:24,138 --> 00:04:25,598
Mark, you up there?

66
00:04:56,458 --> 00:04:57,603
Hey, Al!

67
00:04:57,897 --> 00:04:59,785
Al, pan that lamp around.

68
00:05:23,945 --> 00:05:25,800
All right, who isn't ready?

69
00:05:26,345 --> 00:05:28,582
Good. Let's shoot this one.

70
00:05:28,778 --> 00:05:32,127
Okay, we're going, people.
Let's all settle down.

71
00:05:32,746 --> 00:05:35,593
- And... roll camera.
- Rolling.

72
00:05:35,786 --> 00:05:38,687
Scene 163 Apple, take three.

73
00:05:38,888 --> 00:05:40,799
Okay, marker!

74
00:05:43,467 --> 00:05:44,579
And action!

75
00:05:46,346 --> 00:05:49,215
Cal, you'll have to give it back.

76
00:05:51,177 --> 00:05:54,887
No, I- I made it for you, Dad.

77
00:05:55,082 --> 00:05:56,194
You'll have to give it back.

78
00:05:57,065 --> 00:06:00,447
- To who? I can't give it back-
- To the people you got it from.

79
00:06:00,904 --> 00:06:02,366
The British Purchasing Agency?

80
00:06:02,569 --> 00:06:03,813
I can't give it back to them.

81
00:06:04,009 --> 00:06:05,537
Then to the farmers you robbed.

82
00:06:05,738 --> 00:06:08,738
We didn't rob anybody, Dad.
We paid two cents a pound...

83
00:06:08,937 --> 00:06:11,839
- Two cents over market for that stuff.
- Cal.

84
00:06:13,288 --> 00:06:15,557
I sign my name...

85
00:06:16,008 --> 00:06:18,791
...and boys go out
and some of them die.

86
00:06:18,986 --> 00:06:21,572
And some live helpless
without arms or legs.

87
00:06:21,770 --> 00:06:24,616
Not one will come back untorn.

88
00:06:24,809 --> 00:06:27,329
Do you think I could take
a profit from that?

89
00:06:29,130 --> 00:06:32,163
I don't want the money, Cal.
I couldn't take it!

90
00:06:33,449 --> 00:06:35,107
But thank you for the thought.

91
00:06:35,306 --> 00:06:37,825
I'll keep it for you.
I'll wrap it up and-

92
00:06:38,024 --> 00:06:41,060
I can't take it! I won't take it!

93
00:06:42,666 --> 00:06:43,614
Son...

94
00:06:44,906 --> 00:06:47,208
...I'd be happy if
you gave me something...

95
00:06:47,466 --> 00:06:49,570
Well, something like your brother.

96
00:06:49,768 --> 00:06:51,656
Something honest and...

97
00:06:52,169 --> 00:06:53,631
...and human and good.

98
00:06:54,762 --> 00:06:56,387
Now, don't be angry, son.

99
00:06:56,585 --> 00:06:59,847
If you want to give me a present,
give me a good life.

100
00:07:00,585 --> 00:07:02,559
That's something I can value.

101
00:07:06,378 --> 00:07:07,938
No, Cal.

102
00:07:15,784 --> 00:07:17,858
No. Damn it!

103
00:07:18,890 --> 00:07:20,319
I'm sorry, IKaz. I'm...

104
00:07:20,522 --> 00:07:21,766
Cut it!

105
00:07:23,178 --> 00:07:25,598
IKaz, may I speak to you
a moment? Privately!

106
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:27,393
Let's not everybody fall apart.

107
00:07:27,624 --> 00:07:29,698
- What's up?
- Why is he trying to hug me?

108
00:07:29,897 --> 00:07:34,337
It's infuriating! What he's supposed
to do is turn from me and exit.

109
00:07:34,537 --> 00:07:36,130
That is what-

110
00:07:36,329 --> 00:07:38,402
The last moment is mine.

111
00:07:38,633 --> 00:07:41,503
- I understand.
- He's humiliating my character.

112
00:07:41,705 --> 00:07:45,251
- I'll talk to him and take care of it.
- Please do.

113
00:07:49,929 --> 00:07:52,864
He'll be fine.
He's right where we want him.

114
00:07:53,065 --> 00:07:55,587
But I need one more.
You got another one in you?

115
00:07:55,786 --> 00:07:58,339
You just let me know
when you're ready, okay?

116
00:07:58,538 --> 00:08:01,220
This time, try to kiss him.

117
00:08:04,456 --> 00:08:05,602
Raymond.

118
00:08:10,889 --> 00:08:14,402
- I've talked to him. He's very sorry.
- I should think.

119
00:08:14,601 --> 00:08:17,503
I don't know what to do either.
I need your help.

120
00:08:17,706 --> 00:08:19,299
- If you could do me one favor...
- What?

121
00:08:19,497 --> 00:08:23,358
If you could stay in the scene
and react in character.

122
00:08:23,560 --> 00:08:25,927
No matter what he does, wait
for me to yell, "Cut. "

123
00:08:26,120 --> 00:08:28,062
You have no idea how difficult it is.

124
00:08:28,264 --> 00:08:30,153
- He's so unprofessional.
- He's a young man.

125
00:08:30,345 --> 00:08:33,412
- Yes, he is.
- You're a brilliant actor. Help him.

126
00:08:33,610 --> 00:08:36,707
Help him. Help me because
I don't know what else to do.

127
00:08:36,905 --> 00:08:38,279
All right, all right, all right.

128
00:08:38,665 --> 00:08:42,822
Thank you. Everybody, let's take it
from Adam's line "I sign my name"...

129
00:08:43,017 --> 00:08:45,865
...right through Cal's exit
and no stops, no matter what!

130
00:08:46,057 --> 00:08:48,423
Okay, everyone,
back to one, back to one!

131
00:08:48,616 --> 00:08:52,097
- "I sign my name" right to the end.
- All right.

132
00:09:05,449 --> 00:09:07,871
- Let's go. Quickly.
- Roll camera.

133
00:09:08,585 --> 00:09:11,236
Scene 163 Apple, take four.

134
00:09:12,200 --> 00:09:14,110
- Slate it.
- Marker!

135
00:09:17,257 --> 00:09:18,206
And action.

136
00:09:19,017 --> 00:09:21,832
Cal, I sign my name...

137
00:09:22,025 --> 00:09:24,642
...and boys go out and some die.

138
00:09:24,840 --> 00:09:27,295
And some live helpless
without arms or legs.

139
00:09:27,496 --> 00:09:31,906
Not one will come back untorn. Do you
think I could take a profit from that?

140
00:09:32,105 --> 00:09:35,682
I don't want the money, Cal!
I couldn't take it!

141
00:09:36,104 --> 00:09:37,860
Well, thank you for the thought.

142
00:09:38,057 --> 00:09:39,780
I'll keep it.
I'll wrap it up-

143
00:09:39,977 --> 00:09:42,083
I'll never take it!

144
00:09:43,145 --> 00:09:44,323
Son...

145
00:09:45,737 --> 00:09:48,737
...I'd be happy
if you'd given me something...

146
00:09:49,225 --> 00:09:51,461
...like your brother's given me.

147
00:09:51,656 --> 00:09:53,599
Something honest and human and good.

148
00:09:54,826 --> 00:09:57,095
Oh, don't be angry, son.

149
00:09:57,481 --> 00:10:00,742
If you want to give me a present,
give me a good life.

150
00:10:00,936 --> 00:10:03,041
That's something I could value.

151
00:10:16,744 --> 00:10:17,792
Cal.

152
00:10:19,081 --> 00:10:20,456
Cal, I-

153
00:10:26,697 --> 00:10:27,973
Cal!

154
00:10:38,184 --> 00:10:39,297
Cut!

155
00:10:39,720 --> 00:10:41,630
Print that one, please.

156
00:10:42,217 --> 00:10:44,040
Gets no better than that.

157
00:10:45,481 --> 00:10:46,724
Did you see that?

158
00:10:46,921 --> 00:10:50,336
I did. It was brilliant.
Thank you, Raymond.

159
00:10:51,688 --> 00:10:55,366
Okay, that's it.
Let's print three and four.

160
00:11:18,729 --> 00:11:21,827
"O the raggedy man
He works for Pa

161
00:11:22,025 --> 00:11:24,294
And he's the goodest man you ever saw

162
00:11:24,488 --> 00:11:26,277
He comes to our house every day

163
00:11:28,008 --> 00:11:29,797
Waters the horses and feeds them hay

164
00:11:30,409 --> 00:11:33,256
And he opens the shed
And we just all laugh

165
00:11:33,449 --> 00:11:36,612
When he just drives out
Our little wobbly calf"

166
00:11:37,128 --> 00:11:38,437
What is he saying?

167
00:11:40,008 --> 00:11:41,798
It's a poem, Daddy.

168
00:11:42,281 --> 00:11:44,485
He's memorized three entire verses...

169
00:11:44,682 --> 00:11:46,339
...of James Whitcomb Riley's
"Raggedy Man. "

170
00:11:46,760 --> 00:11:48,996
I am trying to read my paper.

171
00:11:51,336 --> 00:11:53,192
It's a lovely poem, Win.

172
00:11:53,385 --> 00:11:56,254
Fine, you two take the front room.

173
00:12:03,656 --> 00:12:05,184
It's not you, honey.

174
00:12:05,385 --> 00:12:08,614
Daddy's upset with me.
Now, he loves you.

175
00:12:08,809 --> 00:12:11,939
Come on, come here.
It's not your fault, Jimmy.

176
00:12:14,503 --> 00:12:17,701
- It was a long time ago.
- I need a place by myself.

177
00:12:17,897 --> 00:12:19,937
- But I'll be lonely.
- A place where I'm being respected.

178
00:12:20,138 --> 00:12:23,453
Please don't leave me, Win. Please!

179
00:12:46,856 --> 00:12:48,579
You asleep, Jimmy?

180
00:12:49,064 --> 00:12:50,176
No.

181
00:12:52,743 --> 00:12:56,128
- Jimmy, I have to go away for a while.
- Where, Mama?

182
00:12:56,362 --> 00:12:58,335
I have to go to the hospital.

183
00:13:04,168 --> 00:13:05,116
Why?

184
00:13:06,089 --> 00:13:08,358
Because I'm not well.

185
00:13:09,384 --> 00:13:11,718
The doctors, they need to...

186
00:13:16,104 --> 00:13:18,691
They need to do some things
to make me get better.

187
00:13:19,785 --> 00:13:20,994
Can I go with you?

188
00:13:21,288 --> 00:13:23,295
I wish you could.

189
00:13:24,264 --> 00:13:27,461
Who's gonna get me up for school?
Who's staying with me?

190
00:13:27,655 --> 00:13:28,604
Daddy.

191
00:13:32,905 --> 00:13:34,563
Daddy doesn't like me anymore.

192
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:37,892
No, of course he does.
He loves you.

193
00:13:38,184 --> 00:13:39,678
He won't hug me.

194
00:13:40,328 --> 00:13:44,191
Listen, Daddy's not mad at you, Jimmy.

195
00:13:44,904 --> 00:13:49,159
Just keep showing Daddy
your love and he'll love you back.

196
00:13:51,784 --> 00:13:54,174
It's not Daddy's fault, Jimmy.

197
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:00,327
Now go to sleep.

198
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:02,277
I love you.

199
00:14:47,239 --> 00:14:50,022
I was nine years old
when my mother died.

200
00:14:50,344 --> 00:14:52,254
My grandmother Emma
came out to Los Angeles...

201
00:14:52,456 --> 00:14:55,653
...to bring my mother's body
back to Indiana for the funeral.

202
00:14:55,848 --> 00:14:58,237
I think it would be better
if you came with us now-

203
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,512
I can't do that, Mother.

204
00:15:01,064 --> 00:15:03,202
- The boy is so upset.
- I can't leave work just now.

205
00:15:03,400 --> 00:15:05,407
I really can't.
I'll be there at the funeral.

206
00:15:05,608 --> 00:15:07,300
All aboard!

207
00:15:15,272 --> 00:15:16,832
Take good care of your grandma, Jim.

208
00:15:18,664 --> 00:15:22,046
Winton, you shouldn't
take this out on the boy.

209
00:15:22,247 --> 00:15:24,102
Now, for God's sake, give him a kiss.

210
00:15:24,743 --> 00:15:27,613
Say something encouraging.

211
00:15:33,160 --> 00:15:36,160
I'll be coming out to Indiana
in a couple of days, Jim.

212
00:15:40,455 --> 00:15:42,278
All aboard!

213
00:15:55,303 --> 00:15:56,351
You gotta go, Jim.

214
00:16:07,208 --> 00:16:08,997
All aboard, please.

215
00:16:38,087 --> 00:16:39,167
Jimmy?

216
00:16:40,103 --> 00:16:41,086
Jimmy.

217
00:16:42,025 --> 00:16:45,734
No, thanks, Grandma.
I'll go sit with her.

218
00:17:09,767 --> 00:17:11,261
I'm right here with you...

219
00:17:11,463 --> 00:17:14,529
...so don't worry about nothing, okay?

220
00:17:14,727 --> 00:17:19,168
Can you hear me?
Mama, can you hear me?

221
00:17:26,343 --> 00:17:29,278
My father never came
to my mother's funeral.

222
00:17:29,479 --> 00:17:32,196
In fact, he never came
to Indiana at all.

223
00:17:32,583 --> 00:17:35,682
I moved in with my Aunt Hortense
and Uncle Marcus.

224
00:17:37,960 --> 00:17:40,611
Son, you can't stay here.

225
00:18:18,408 --> 00:18:20,262
You almost got me
that time, Mr. Walther.

226
00:18:20,807 --> 00:18:23,141
Yeah, one of these days, James.

227
00:18:24,136 --> 00:18:26,405
You got anything for me from California?

228
00:18:27,719 --> 00:18:29,574
No, just the usual.

229
00:18:30,087 --> 00:18:32,258
Want ads, circulars.

230
00:18:33,095 --> 00:18:34,044
I'm sorry.

231
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:36,127
Yeah.

232
00:18:46,343 --> 00:18:49,987
Our next graduate holds
the Grant County record...

233
00:18:50,183 --> 00:18:51,939
...for the pole vault.

234
00:18:52,135 --> 00:18:54,339
He is a four-letter man...

235
00:18:55,304 --> 00:18:57,693
...an outstanding dramatic speaker...

236
00:18:57,895 --> 00:19:02,019
...and as everybody knows,
a fine actor.

237
00:19:12,936 --> 00:19:16,416
And he will soon be off
to study Business Administration...

238
00:19:16,807 --> 00:19:21,444
...at Santa Monica
Community College in California.

239
00:19:21,895 --> 00:19:25,375
James Byron Dean!

240
00:20:12,935 --> 00:20:15,040
Jim, is that you?

241
00:20:18,343 --> 00:20:19,553
Come on in.

242
00:20:24,743 --> 00:20:27,199
Thank you for letting me
stay here with you.

243
00:20:27,464 --> 00:20:31,042
You can stay here
a month or so, till you're on your feet.

244
00:20:31,239 --> 00:20:33,061
It's fine with us.

245
00:20:33,287 --> 00:20:34,847
This is Ethel.

246
00:20:35,463 --> 00:20:36,477
Oh, hi.

247
00:20:36,999 --> 00:20:40,544
Your dad's told me so much about
you. I'm glad to meet you.

248
00:20:40,743 --> 00:20:43,558
Ethel's my wife, Jim. We're married.

249
00:20:45,767 --> 00:20:47,174
You're married.

250
00:20:47,976 --> 00:20:50,114
That- That's great.

251
00:20:51,463 --> 00:20:53,699
Let me show you the guest room.

252
00:20:53,894 --> 00:20:55,073
I mean, your room.

253
00:21:08,040 --> 00:21:10,428
I hated business school.

254
00:21:11,303 --> 00:21:13,856
Felt like I was wasting my time.

255
00:21:14,695 --> 00:21:17,890
I'd done some acting in high school
and I loved it.

256
00:21:18,759 --> 00:21:22,142
And more than anything,
I wanted to study acting.

257
00:21:22,343 --> 00:21:25,061
Oh, Winnie. Oh, Winnie.

258
00:21:54,374 --> 00:21:55,902
Acting?

259
00:21:56,102 --> 00:21:58,044
Like in plays and movies?

260
00:22:00,744 --> 00:22:01,954
Yes, sir.

261
00:22:07,815 --> 00:22:10,237
How you planning on making a living?

262
00:22:11,687 --> 00:22:12,897
Acting.

263
00:22:17,158 --> 00:22:20,837
You are a dreamer.
Just like your mama.

264
00:22:22,983 --> 00:22:25,088
That wasn't our understanding.

265
00:22:27,015 --> 00:22:28,956
You stay in business school...

266
00:22:30,053 --> 00:22:31,712
...and you can stay here.

267
00:22:33,223 --> 00:22:35,557
But you study acting...

268
00:22:39,144 --> 00:22:41,052
...you're on your own.

269
00:22:42,663 --> 00:22:44,638
Next in is...

270
00:22:44,839 --> 00:22:49,116
...Byron and/or James Dean?

271
00:22:49,319 --> 00:22:50,267
Over here, kid.

272
00:22:53,286 --> 00:22:55,676
Which is your real name?
Byron or James?

273
00:22:56,263 --> 00:22:57,376
Well...

274
00:22:58,183 --> 00:23:00,605
What do you think is better
for an actor?

275
00:23:01,319 --> 00:23:03,773
Go with your real name. Less confusing.

276
00:23:05,414 --> 00:23:06,559
What can I do for you?

277
00:23:08,423 --> 00:23:09,917
I want to study here...

278
00:23:10,182 --> 00:23:13,313
...in your professional acting class,
Mr. Whitmore.

279
00:23:14,407 --> 00:23:15,814
Are you any good?

280
00:23:19,015 --> 00:23:23,008
Well, I did a couple plays
in high school...

281
00:23:23,719 --> 00:23:25,857
...and people said
I was pretty good, but I...

282
00:23:26,407 --> 00:23:29,504
Sir, I don't want to be just good.

283
00:23:29,702 --> 00:23:31,197
I want to be great.

284
00:23:34,279 --> 00:23:35,555
Got any money?

285
00:23:37,543 --> 00:23:38,688
No.

286
00:23:39,398 --> 00:23:40,510
I sure don't.

287
00:23:41,062 --> 00:23:42,819
Great ones never do.

288
00:23:43,014 --> 00:23:45,251
All right, kid. You're in.

289
00:24:06,182 --> 00:24:09,565
It's 12 a week, man. Cash, no checks.

290
00:24:19,815 --> 00:24:20,960
I'll take it.

291
00:24:24,679 --> 00:24:27,994
So how come you got a card
up at Whitmore's studio?

292
00:24:28,197 --> 00:24:29,604
You an actor?

293
00:24:31,079 --> 00:24:33,796
Next to Brando,
I'm the world's greatest actor.

294
00:24:34,599 --> 00:24:36,006
Who's Brando?

295
00:24:36,422 --> 00:24:38,332
Jimmy, Billy, up front.

296
00:24:38,535 --> 00:24:41,251
Billy owns a watch repair shop.

297
00:24:41,446 --> 00:24:44,065
Jimmy's picking up a watch
that he cleaned.

298
00:24:44,262 --> 00:24:46,335
Billy, come here. Come here.

299
00:24:49,159 --> 00:24:52,453
You know it's stolen,
you called the cops.

300
00:24:53,382 --> 00:24:57,158
You gotta keep Jimmy here till they
arrive so you can collect the reward.

301
00:24:57,479 --> 00:24:59,868
Don't let him go. Okay?

302
00:25:05,221 --> 00:25:06,235
All right.

303
00:25:06,918 --> 00:25:09,440
You have an appointment
in 15 minutes...

304
00:25:10,119 --> 00:25:12,640
...to deliver this watch
across town to a buyer...

305
00:25:12,839 --> 00:25:14,813
...for $2000 cash.

306
00:25:15,014 --> 00:25:19,041
You want to get the watch fast.
You need the money, Jimmy.

307
00:25:19,622 --> 00:25:22,273
- All right. You both got the setup?
- Yeah.

308
00:25:27,399 --> 00:25:28,925
Whenever you're ready.

309
00:25:35,207 --> 00:25:36,636
Hi.

310
00:25:37,543 --> 00:25:40,411
I'm here to pick up that watch
right there in the case.

311
00:25:41,093 --> 00:25:43,395
It's not ready yet.
Just give me a minute.

312
00:25:44,006 --> 00:25:45,054
No, that's fine.

313
00:25:45,286 --> 00:25:46,661
No, no, no. Stay cool.

314
00:25:46,855 --> 00:25:47,869
Give me the watch, man!

315
00:25:48,103 --> 00:25:49,510
Okay, give me a minute.

316
00:25:49,703 --> 00:25:50,912
Hey!

317
00:25:54,630 --> 00:25:57,598
- Hey! IKnock it off!
- Come on, you stinking black!

318
00:25:57,798 --> 00:25:59,042
Jimmy, knock it off!

319
00:25:59,238 --> 00:26:01,474
- IKnock it off, Jimmy!
- I'm gonna kill you!

320
00:26:01,734 --> 00:26:04,417
Jimmy, knock it off. Jimmy!

321
00:26:05,094 --> 00:26:08,094
Hey. Enough, enough.

322
00:26:09,223 --> 00:26:10,335
Enough.

323
00:26:20,518 --> 00:26:23,835
Stanislavski, you're next. Come on in.

324
00:26:34,599 --> 00:26:36,486
You get into a lot of fights?

325
00:26:36,678 --> 00:26:38,564
No, not a lot.

326
00:26:38,917 --> 00:26:39,866
You will...

327
00:26:40,261 --> 00:26:43,296
...if you let yourself go
over the edge like you just did.

328
00:26:43,719 --> 00:26:46,468
Jimmy, acting is acting.

329
00:26:46,663 --> 00:26:50,404
You can't get confused.
You gotta know where to draw the line.

330
00:26:52,453 --> 00:26:55,651
Yeah, I know. I know.

331
00:26:56,998 --> 00:26:58,492
I mean, it was good, right?

332
00:27:00,102 --> 00:27:01,444
Yeah, yeah.

333
00:27:02,118 --> 00:27:03,492
Yes, it was good.

334
00:27:03,686 --> 00:27:05,377
Wait, Mr. Whitmore.

335
00:27:06,022 --> 00:27:07,932
I want to ask you something.

336
00:27:11,366 --> 00:27:13,787
Do you think I got the goods
to be a real actor?

337
00:27:17,157 --> 00:27:18,717
Yes, I do, Jimmy.

338
00:27:20,326 --> 00:27:22,082
Yes, I do.

339
00:27:25,830 --> 00:27:27,935
I decided to move to New York.

340
00:27:28,261 --> 00:27:32,572
Every actor I cared about,
Brando, Clift, even Whitmore...

341
00:27:32,774 --> 00:27:34,846
...all worked in New York.

342
00:27:35,046 --> 00:27:37,346
New York was big and lonely...

343
00:27:37,541 --> 00:27:39,004
...and I loved it.

344
00:27:39,238 --> 00:27:43,099
Being a struggling actor in New York
in the 1950s was the best.

345
00:27:43,303 --> 00:27:44,928
The right place at the right time.

346
00:27:46,374 --> 00:27:49,243
I stopped worrying about
my mother and father for a while.

347
00:27:49,605 --> 00:27:51,263
I was dead broke.

348
00:27:51,909 --> 00:27:53,119
It didn't matter.

349
00:27:53,413 --> 00:27:54,875
I was home.

350
00:27:56,999 --> 00:27:59,203
Off the stage! Off the stage!
Let's go!

351
00:27:59,398 --> 00:28:03,805
Next five numbers. 120 through 124.

352
00:28:04,422 --> 00:28:05,534
Shut up!

353
00:28:05,734 --> 00:28:08,101
Shut up! I want to see those numbers!

354
00:28:08,326 --> 00:28:10,016
I want to see them today!

355
00:28:10,246 --> 00:28:13,660
123, 120, 124!

356
00:28:13,861 --> 00:28:17,310
Today, today! Thank you.

357
00:28:20,839 --> 00:28:21,984
Smoke?

358
00:28:22,182 --> 00:28:23,197
Yeah.

359
00:28:24,198 --> 00:28:26,433
- Thanks, man.
- No problem.

360
00:28:27,622 --> 00:28:28,898
What's your name?

361
00:28:29,093 --> 00:28:30,816
I can't decide.

362
00:28:31,141 --> 00:28:32,964
What are your choices?

363
00:28:33,158 --> 00:28:36,355
Well, I got James Dean, Jimmy Dean...

364
00:28:36,902 --> 00:28:38,690
...or Byron Dean.

365
00:28:38,886 --> 00:28:40,609
Which one's your real name?

366
00:28:40,806 --> 00:28:43,490
James. Byron's my middle name.

367
00:28:44,134 --> 00:28:45,989
Go with your real name.

368
00:28:47,334 --> 00:28:49,155
- You think?
- I know.

369
00:28:49,349 --> 00:28:52,927
Jimmy's an 8-year-old boy
and Byron's a dead poet with a clubfoot.

370
00:28:54,117 --> 00:28:55,973
And James is king.

371
00:28:57,094 --> 00:28:58,043
What's your name?

372
00:28:58,246 --> 00:28:59,293
Martin Landau.

373
00:29:02,405 --> 00:29:03,517
Where you from?

374
00:29:03,717 --> 00:29:05,789
Why? You wanna come home
and meet my mom?

375
00:29:06,021 --> 00:29:07,166
Yeah, can she cook?

376
00:29:07,365 --> 00:29:09,919
- You like matzo ball soup?
- My favorite.

377
00:29:10,182 --> 00:29:12,931
You're invited.
Where you living?

378
00:29:13,126 --> 00:29:15,613
Some dirt-hole rented room.

379
00:29:15,814 --> 00:29:16,828
Let's go, fellas.

380
00:29:17,061 --> 00:29:21,470
125 through 129, you're up!

381
00:29:21,798 --> 00:29:22,943
What number you got?

382
00:29:23,142 --> 00:29:24,865
231.

383
00:29:25,061 --> 00:29:26,174
I'm 216.

384
00:29:26,725 --> 00:29:29,343
Let's cut out, man.
Cattle calls are for losers.

385
00:29:29,541 --> 00:29:30,468
Yeah?

386
00:29:30,661 --> 00:29:32,964
Unless you got an agent sending you in,
you're kidding yourself.

387
00:29:33,159 --> 00:29:34,271
All right.

388
00:29:44,358 --> 00:29:45,470
Thanks.

389
00:29:46,726 --> 00:29:47,806
You got an agent?

390
00:29:48,005 --> 00:29:49,566
If I had an agent...

391
00:29:51,301 --> 00:29:54,367
...would I be blowing my time
with a goof like you?

392
00:29:54,917 --> 00:29:55,998
Come on.

393
00:29:56,199 --> 00:29:59,133
Hey, who was Brando's agent
in New York?

394
00:29:59,877 --> 00:30:01,088
Louis.

395
00:30:01,381 --> 00:30:02,308
What?

396
00:30:02,501 --> 00:30:06,047
I'll take him on.
I have a hunch I can sell him.

397
00:30:06,245 --> 00:30:08,800
To who? To The Ringling Brothers?

398
00:30:08,998 --> 00:30:11,137
Jane, he's too strange!

399
00:30:11,334 --> 00:30:14,497
It's a "strange" people
won't get out of their minds.

400
00:30:14,693 --> 00:30:19,035
I think he's a star.
Let me see what I can do with him.

401
00:30:21,286 --> 00:30:24,830
All right. You do it on your own time,
not on my time.

402
00:30:26,020 --> 00:30:27,876
What am I gonna do with you?

403
00:30:39,652 --> 00:30:40,700
Bring your chair over.

404
00:30:49,542 --> 00:30:52,924
You put "Leads only. "
You can't just audition for leads.

405
00:30:53,573 --> 00:30:54,653
Why not?

406
00:30:55,557 --> 00:30:57,565
For one thing, you've got to eat.

407
00:30:58,342 --> 00:31:00,196
No, Miss Deacy...

408
00:31:00,676 --> 00:31:05,117
Look, I only want to audition
for important parts.

409
00:31:05,541 --> 00:31:08,128
I mean, parts that I care about.

410
00:31:08,678 --> 00:31:10,588
Even if I have to starve.

411
00:31:15,780 --> 00:31:16,991
Fine.

412
00:31:20,006 --> 00:31:21,696
Thank you, Miss Deacy.

413
00:31:24,198 --> 00:31:25,375
I'm a...

414
00:31:26,405 --> 00:31:28,412
I'm a really lucky guy.

415
00:31:29,605 --> 00:31:31,132
I've got the best agent in the world.

416
00:31:31,942 --> 00:31:34,211
Get me those 8 x 10s.

417
00:31:45,574 --> 00:31:46,687
Hi.

418
00:31:47,077 --> 00:31:49,149
You work here?

419
00:31:49,701 --> 00:31:51,130
I don't work here.

420
00:31:51,621 --> 00:31:52,635
So...

421
00:31:53,541 --> 00:31:55,166
...you're a writer or something?

422
00:31:55,365 --> 00:31:56,576
You're an actor?

423
00:31:57,158 --> 00:31:58,783
Jane Deacy just signed me.

424
00:31:58,980 --> 00:32:01,217
Well, congratulations.

425
00:32:02,277 --> 00:32:03,619
Are you an actor?

426
00:32:03,813 --> 00:32:05,918
Actress. I'm an actress.

427
00:32:06,117 --> 00:32:08,573
What are you writing,
Miss Actress?

428
00:32:08,774 --> 00:32:10,236
Audition scene.

429
00:32:10,885 --> 00:32:12,314
Yeah? Who wrote it?

430
00:32:12,517 --> 00:32:14,306
That's what I'm trying to do.

431
00:32:14,500 --> 00:32:16,093
Can I see it?

432
00:32:16,293 --> 00:32:17,700
Yeah.

433
00:32:18,052 --> 00:32:20,127
Well, this is the first page.

434
00:32:33,382 --> 00:32:36,381
- So?
- Yeah, this is good.

435
00:32:36,676 --> 00:32:38,717
What are you auditioning for?

436
00:32:38,917 --> 00:32:39,866
The Studio.

437
00:32:42,181 --> 00:32:43,391
Actors Studio?

438
00:32:43,621 --> 00:32:44,832
Yeah.

439
00:32:46,533 --> 00:32:47,776
Wow.

440
00:32:48,357 --> 00:32:51,935
Brando's like some kind
of lifetime member there, right?

441
00:32:52,740 --> 00:32:53,689
Yeah.

442
00:32:55,205 --> 00:32:56,667
What's your name?

443
00:32:57,061 --> 00:32:58,654
No, wait, don't, don't, don't.

444
00:32:59,493 --> 00:33:01,697
- Why not?
- I don't know.

445
00:33:02,341 --> 00:33:03,769
How about...

446
00:33:05,893 --> 00:33:08,643
How about I take you out tonight?

447
00:33:08,998 --> 00:33:11,364
I'll give you a ride on my motorcycle.

448
00:33:12,644 --> 00:33:15,808
And then after I take you home
after the movie...

449
00:33:16,453 --> 00:33:19,868
...when I lean in to kiss,
you can tell me then.

450
00:33:23,173 --> 00:33:24,285
You got a scene partner?

451
00:33:25,124 --> 00:33:26,651
I did.

452
00:33:27,621 --> 00:33:28,766
Come on!

453
00:33:32,198 --> 00:33:34,433
- I can't...
- Come on!

454
00:33:35,174 --> 00:33:36,515
- Come on!
- Let's do it!

455
00:33:36,741 --> 00:33:37,952
Let's go!

456
00:33:43,301 --> 00:33:44,731
Oh, this is great.

457
00:33:57,925 --> 00:33:58,907
What's the matter?

458
00:33:59,141 --> 00:34:00,318
White.

459
00:34:00,677 --> 00:34:02,204
Christine White.

460
00:34:02,501 --> 00:34:03,777
My name.

461
00:34:04,900 --> 00:34:06,275
Good to meet you.

462
00:34:09,222 --> 00:34:13,477
Okay, I need Morty Chase
and Stanley Rushton.

463
00:34:13,701 --> 00:34:16,122
Yes, gentlemen, please. Thank you.

464
00:34:16,325 --> 00:34:18,975
Ah, excuse me. Excuse me.

465
00:34:19,781 --> 00:34:20,960
Who's watching the auditions?

466
00:34:21,158 --> 00:34:24,092
Kazan, Lee Strasberg,
and Cheryl Crawford.

467
00:34:25,701 --> 00:34:27,075
- They're all here.
- Who?

468
00:34:27,300 --> 00:34:30,715
Strasberg, Elia Kazan
and Cheryl Crawford.

469
00:34:30,916 --> 00:34:32,674
- Oh, my God.
- Good.

470
00:34:39,077 --> 00:34:41,532
Hey, that's my prop! Don't drink it!

471
00:34:41,732 --> 00:34:45,474
Jimmy. Jimmy, stop! Come on.

472
00:34:46,500 --> 00:34:48,769
You just drank my prop, Jimmy.

473
00:34:48,964 --> 00:34:51,583
Okay, Christine White and James Dean?

474
00:34:51,781 --> 00:34:52,795
Yes, that's us.

475
00:34:52,997 --> 00:34:55,931
- You're on next. Are you ready?
- We're ready. Thank you.

476
00:34:56,197 --> 00:34:57,626
Oh, my God.

477
00:34:58,820 --> 00:34:59,900
Where are your glasses?

478
00:35:00,101 --> 00:35:01,508
No, they're wrong for my character.

479
00:35:01,700 --> 00:35:03,805
Wait, can you see anything
without your glasses?

480
00:35:04,004 --> 00:35:06,338
Yeah, I see fine.
What do you think, man? How-

481
00:35:07,140 --> 00:35:09,213
Yeah, very, very funny.
Put on your glasses.

482
00:35:09,413 --> 00:35:11,584
I can't, Chris.
They're back at my place.

483
00:35:11,781 --> 00:35:13,275
Why'd you leave them at your place?

484
00:35:13,477 --> 00:35:16,379
They're wrong for my character.
I don't want to be tempted to use them.

485
00:35:16,581 --> 00:35:18,403
Dean, White, let's go!

486
00:35:19,236 --> 00:35:20,481
Oh, sorry. I didn't-

487
00:35:20,678 --> 00:35:23,710
That's a chair.
You're apologizing to a chair.

488
00:35:24,932 --> 00:35:26,590
I'm telling you, Jimmy, you never know.

489
00:35:26,820 --> 00:35:28,643
Look at me when I auditioned
for Tennessee Williams.

490
00:35:28,837 --> 00:35:30,430
I thought I was terrible.

491
00:35:31,781 --> 00:35:33,537
You were terrible.
You didn't get the part.

492
00:35:33,733 --> 00:35:35,521
It's just a detail.

493
00:35:36,677 --> 00:35:37,625
Hi.

494
00:35:37,860 --> 00:35:39,802
I'm Rogers Brackett.

495
00:35:40,196 --> 00:35:42,530
Oh, God. The director?

496
00:35:43,684 --> 00:35:47,776
A mutual friend tells me that
you're enormously talented.

497
00:35:50,661 --> 00:35:51,838
Yeah, I guess.

498
00:35:53,317 --> 00:35:57,026
I know of something that
you just might be right for.

499
00:35:57,220 --> 00:36:00,635
A TV drama. It's a very good role.

500
00:36:00,836 --> 00:36:03,684
So... would you like to audition?

501
00:36:04,580 --> 00:36:05,858
Yeah, sure.

502
00:36:06,565 --> 00:36:10,525
There's a party at my place tonight.
How would you feel about stopping by?

503
00:36:11,460 --> 00:36:13,599
We could chat about the project.

504
00:36:14,692 --> 00:36:16,285
There'll be some interesting men there.

505
00:36:19,044 --> 00:36:21,727
Yeah, that sounds like a ball.

506
00:36:23,300 --> 00:36:24,249
Here's my card.

507
00:36:25,893 --> 00:36:27,387
Why don't you come by late?

508
00:36:27,588 --> 00:36:29,628
Say midnight?

509
00:36:31,141 --> 00:36:33,377
Yeah, midnight. That...

510
00:36:33,604 --> 00:36:34,814
Perfect.

511
00:36:35,172 --> 00:36:37,212
Good. See you later.

512
00:36:38,244 --> 00:36:39,520
Right on.

513
00:36:41,764 --> 00:36:44,580
That man's a class-A faygalah,
you know that, right?

514
00:36:45,541 --> 00:36:49,370
Yeah, the man's a class-A faygalah
with a paying job.

515
00:37:08,580 --> 00:37:11,231
Oh, Lord, you look like Hamlet!

516
00:37:11,684 --> 00:37:13,058
Come in.

517
00:37:30,404 --> 00:37:31,648
I'm drumming. Go to hell!

518
00:37:31,843 --> 00:37:34,843
Come on, Jimmy. It's important!

519
00:37:36,100 --> 00:37:38,914
